Do people that use credit cards in making
routine payments

2
00:00:05,680 --> 00:00:09,440
differ in the way they make purchase evaluations
than people that routinely

3
00:00:09,440 --> 00:00:10,440
use checks?

4
00:00:10,440 --> 00:00:13,780
That was a question that I was trying to address
in a paper that I published

5
00:00:13,780 --> 00:00:18,920
in 2001 in the Journal of Consumer Research.

6
00:00:18,920 --> 00:00:21,679
That paper had two experiments of which we'll
focus

7
00:00:21,679 --> 00:00:24,390
on one in this module.

8
00:00:24,390 --> 00:00:27,500
The goal, as I said, of that paper was to
test whether the routine use of

9
00:00:27,500 --> 00:00:31,410
credit cards influences future spending and
to identify the

10
00:00:31,410 --> 00:00:35,660
mechanisms that underlie these differences.

11
00:00:35,660 --> 00:00:39,780
In this particular experiment, study one,
consumers who paid for past

12
00:00:39,780 --> 00:00:43,620
expenses by credit cards will be more likely
to purchase an additional

13
00:00:43,620 --> 00:00:47,800
discretionary product as compared with consumers
who paid for the same

14
00:00:47,800 --> 00:00:51,890
expense by check, all other things being held
constant, was the

15
00:00:51,890 --> 00:00:56,130
hypothesis that I was looking to test.

16
00:00:56,130 --> 00:00:59,070
This was a lab experiment in which participants
made hypothetical

17
00:00:59,070 --> 00:01:02,510
decisions in a hypothetical context.

18
00:01:02,510 --> 00:01:08,670
The experiment used three factors each of
which had two levels.

19
00:01:08,670 --> 00:01:13,729
The first was payment mechanism in which participants
were either in a

20
00:01:13,729 --> 00:01:17,960
credit card condition or a check condition.

21
00:01:17,960 --> 00:01:21,460
The second factor was feedback.

22
00:01:21,460 --> 00:01:24,970
Some participants were given a running total
of the cumulative expenses to

23
00:01:24,970 --> 00:01:30,219
date as they made payments while others were
not.

24
00:01:30,219 --> 00:01:34,850
And finally, the third factor was a credit
limit.

25
00:01:34,850 --> 00:01:38,289
All participants were told that they had a
credit card.

26
00:01:38,289 --> 00:01:43,280
In one set of conditions they were told that
the credit limit was $3,000,

27
00:01:43,280 --> 00:01:47,289
in a second set that it was $8,000.

28
00:01:47,289 --> 00:01:52,429
160 students at a university participated
in this experiment.

29
00:01:52,429 --> 00:01:57,140
And they were randomly assigned to a total
of eight conditions that were

30
00:01:57,140 --> 00:02:02,500
formed by completely crossing two payment
conditions with two feedback

31
00:02:02,500 --> 00:02:08,979
conditions with two credit limit conditions
for a total of eight

32
00:02:08,979 --> 00:02:11,880
different experimental conditions.

33
00:02:11,880 --> 00:02:15,010
All participants were asked to imagine that
they had a job that

34
00:02:15,010 --> 00:02:16,880
paid $3,000 a month.

35
00:02:16,880 --> 00:02:21,310
They had bank accounts as well as a credit
card with a given limit.

36
00:02:21,310 --> 00:02:25,540
And then, every participant was shown 30 index
cards with expenses that they

37
00:02:25,540 --> 00:02:28,610
would incur in a typical month.

38
00:02:28,610 --> 00:02:34,930
Now, the idea behind this experiment was to
simply recreate the mechanics

39
00:02:34,930 --> 00:02:39,250
of payment that an individual would go through
in a given month over the

40
00:02:39,250 --> 00:02:43,850
space of 30 days in a lab setting where the
same process took about an

41
00:02:43,850 --> 00:02:46,300
hour or an hour and a half.

42
00:02:46,300 --> 00:02:50,470
So then, participants saw each index card.

43
00:02:50,470 --> 00:02:56,610
They actually made "payments," in inverted
quotes, for 12 of these

44
00:02:56,610 --> 00:03:03,270
expenses either by writing 12 checks or by
signing 12 credit card receipts.

45
00:03:03,270 --> 00:03:08,820
And I'll show you exactly what these stimulus
look like in a minute.

46
00:03:08,820 --> 00:03:12,770
At the end of this entire process--
about an hour, hour and a half--

47
00:03:12,770 --> 00:03:16,590
participants answered the final question,
which contained the

48
00:03:16,590 --> 00:03:17,960
dependent variable.

49
00:03:17,960 --> 00:03:24,020
They were given some information on a box
CD set by a favorite artist with a

50
00:03:24,020 --> 00:03:26,430
specific price and a whole bunch of attributes.

51
00:03:26,430 --> 00:03:30,210
And they were asked to indicate on a ten-point
scale whether, in fact, they

52
00:03:30,210 --> 00:03:33,460
would make this purchase given all of the
other expenses that they have

53
00:03:33,460 --> 00:03:37,090
incurred in this month.

54
00:03:37,090 --> 00:03:42,100
Here's what the average index card looked
like.

55
00:03:42,100 --> 00:03:47,890
For example, in this particular case, on March
9 the participant had a

56
00:03:47,890 --> 00:03:55,310
telephone bill of $100.72, which was either
paid by check or by credit

57
00:03:55,310 --> 00:03:57,600
card, depending on which condition they were
in.

58
00:03:57,600 --> 00:04:01,310
And then, they had a cash purchase of coffee
and bagel for breakfast, which

59
00:04:01,310 --> 00:04:03,260
was paid by cash.

60
00:04:03,260 --> 00:04:06,180
And of course, that was not part of the manipulation.

61
00:04:06,180 --> 00:04:10,640
If, in fact, the participant was in the check
condition, they would then

62
00:04:10,640 --> 00:04:13,300
see a check like this one.

63
00:04:13,300 --> 00:04:16,150
And they would actually need to complete the
check after seeing this

64
00:04:16,150 --> 00:04:24,810
index card by filling up the name of the payee,
there, putting in a date,

65
00:04:24,810 --> 00:04:36,110
writing down the full amount in numbers, as
well as words--

66
00:04:36,110 --> 00:04:39,169
obviously in better handwriting than this.

67
00:04:39,169 --> 00:04:44,090
And they would sign it and drop it in the
box.

68
00:04:44,090 --> 00:04:48,949
If in fact, they were in a credit card condition,
they would see a

69
00:04:48,949 --> 00:04:51,900
counterfoil pretty much that you would see
