72
00:04:57,249 --> 00:05:02,050
And then, they had to put this in the box
along with the other stimulus.

73
00:05:02,050 --> 00:05:06,939
Keep in mind, every participant either paid
for everything by check or

74
00:05:06,939 --> 00:05:11,460
everything by credit card.

75
00:05:11,460 --> 00:05:14,740
The data were analyzed by ANOVA (analysis
of variance) comparing the

76
00:05:14,740 --> 00:05:17,439
mean across all of the conditions that we
talked about.

77
00:05:17,439 --> 00:05:21,159
And we found that purchase intentions varied
as a function of payment

78
00:05:21,159 --> 00:05:24,760
mechanism, credit limit, as well as feedback.

79
00:05:24,760 --> 00:05:31,360
We found a significant main effect of payment
mechanism, feedback, and

80
00:05:31,360 --> 00:05:32,360
credit limit.

81
00:05:32,360 --> 00:05:37,490
In other words, people were more likely on
average to make a purchase

82
00:05:37,490 --> 00:05:41,999
in the credit card condition than the check
condition.

83
00:05:41,999 --> 00:05:46,199
They were less likely to make a purchase when
they received feedback.

84
00:05:46,199 --> 00:05:49,870
And they were more likely to make a purchase
when they had a high credit

85
00:05:49,870 --> 00:05:52,569
limit as compared to a low one.

86
00:05:52,569 --> 00:05:58,629
However, these main effects were qualified
by two-way interactions.

87
00:05:58,629 --> 00:06:00,860
Let's focus for a minute on the first one
of them--

88
00:06:00,860 --> 00:06:05,789
a payment mechanism by feedback interaction.

89
00:06:05,789 --> 00:06:12,360
So if you look at the graph on the right-hand
panel over here.

90
00:06:12,360 --> 00:06:14,440
Here is what you'll see.

91
