98
00:06:43,559 --> 00:06:48,419
This is the case where there was no feedback.

99
00:06:48,419 --> 00:06:50,990
And the credit limit was high.

100
00:06:50,990 --> 00:06:54,819
And under those substances, you'll see that
there is a dramatic difference

101
00:06:54,819 --> 00:07:00,550
between the purchase intention for check and
the purchase intention for

102
00:07:00,550 --> 00:07:01,900
credit cards.

103
00:07:01,900 --> 00:07:08,949
Now if you go from this green line to one
of these lines here, where in fact

104
00:07:08,949 --> 00:07:17,039
you now have the same level of credit limit
but you provide feedback, you

105
00:07:17,039 --> 00:07:21,599
notice that the purchase intention declines.

106
00:07:21,599 --> 00:07:26,199
And when you go from that condition down here
where now, you not only

107
00:07:26,199 --> 00:07:30,509
provide feedback, but also reduce the credit
limit, we get down to our

108
00:07:30,509 --> 00:07:33,339
condition here, which is not significantly
different.

109
00:07:33,339 --> 00:07:37,969
So in somewhat we concluded with this research
was that there were two

110
00:07:37,969 --> 00:07:42,629
factors that seemed to be driving the effect
of credit cards over checks.

111
00:07:42,629 --> 00:07:44,729
One was the fact that there was something
going on

112
00:07:44,729 --> 00:07:46,039
with the credit limit.

113
00:07:46,039 --> 00:07:50,279
The second was the fact that credit cards
didn't give people feedback

114
00:07:50,279 --> 00:07:55,439
because they were--
unlike checks where you wrote down the number,

115
00:07:55,439 --> 00:08:00,229
the opportunity to rehearse
the price paid was very low for credit cards.

116
00:08:00,229 --> 00:08:01,889
So in fact, our conclusion was simple.

117
00:08:01,889 --> 00:08:05,419
Paying for a series of past expenses with
a credit card verses check

118
00:08:05,419 --> 00:08:10,039
increased the purchase intention for an additional
discretionary product.

